ng new paradigms; (2) whether embodiment/robotics must be included in AGI; and (3) how much AI progress will accelerate AI research itself. Key assumptions affecting timelines include continued exponential growth in compute investment, algorithmic efficiency, and human capital in AI R&D — all of which may eventually bottleneck around 2030–2032.\",\n    \"Panelist B\": \"I estimate a 50% chance of AGI by 2047, based on the median of AI experts publishing at top conferences (NIPS/ICML 2021 survey). 'Achieved' means AI that can do every task better or more cheaply than humans. The top disagreements are: (1) whether generalization across domains requires fundamentally different architectures than current models; (2) whether long-horizon agency and recursive self-improvement are necessary components; and (3) how to interpret progress on narrow benchmarks versus genuine cognitive versatility. The timeline is most sensitive to assumptions about whether cognitive bottlenecks (e.g., long-term memory, causal reasoning) can be overcome without new theoretical breakthroughs — current models still lack foundational cognitive machinery.\",\n    \"Panelist C\": \"Using a quantifiable psychometric framework based on the Cattell-Horn-Carroll theory of intelligence, AGI is defined as matching the cognitive versatility and proficiency of a well-educated adult across ten core domains (e.g., reasoning, memory, perception). Current models like GPT-4 score 27%, GPT-5 57% — implying AGI is plausible by 2030 if progress continues. I assign a 60% probability of AGI by 2035. Experts disagree on: (1) whether high-level reasoning under time pressure constitutes AGI, even if other domains lag; (2) whether economic impact (e.g., automating remote work) matters more than cognitive completeness; and (3) whether AI will accelerate its own development. Key assumptions include sustained progress in memory architectures and integration of multi-modal learning — if these stall, timelines extend significantly.\"\n  }\n}"
