performing humans in all tasks better and more cheaply. The main cruxes are: (1) whether cognitive systems can generalize to scientific insight and long-horizon planning; (2) whether robotics will bottleneck progress; and (3) whether economic automation follows automatically from technical feasibility. Key assumptions affecting timelines include continued scaling of compute, avoidance of regulatory or societal disruption, and successful integration of multimodal skills.\",\n    \"Rand Corporation\": \"Expert forecasts have shifted toward the near term (2030s) due to rapid progress, but definitions of AGI vary significantly (e.g., 'performing most economically valuable work'). The lack of definitional clarity drives some disagreement, but even with shared definitions, experts diverge widely. Top cruxes include: (1) how to model discontinuous vs. incremental progress; (2) the role of real-world embodiment and robotics; and (3) whether automation of labor requires full human replacement or merely task substitution. Assumptions that affect timelines include sustained investment, absence of global conflict or regulation, and the feasibility of recursive self-improvement. The key insight is not to predict a single date but to prepare for a range of plausible, high-impact scenarios, using flexible and robust strategies.\",\n    \"AI Impacts / Grace et al.\": \"Based on a 2023 survey of 2,778 AI researchers, the median estimate for 'high-level machine intelligence' (HLMI) — defined as unaided machines outperforming humans in every task better and more cheaply — is a 10% chance by 2027 and 50% by 2047 (13 years earlier than the 2022 estimate). For full automation of labor, the 50% milestone is projected by 2116. This 70-year gap between HLMI and full automation is unexplained and may reflect definitional confusion or behavioral inertia. The top cruxes are: (1) the feasibility of generalization beyond narrow tasks; (2) whether AI can achieve autonomous scientific research; and (3) whether economic and social adoption will lag technical feasibility. Assumptions that affect timelines include continued scaling of models, availability of compute, and absence of major societal or geopolitical disruptions.\"\n  }\n}"
