cture-invariant: gains can come from changing where weights live (on-chip SRAM/NVM), reducing bytes moved (quantization/compression/sparsity/speculative methods), or changing the algorithm; still, 1000× vs a well-optimized H100 remains extraordinary and demands unusually strong proof."}]}, {"topic": "Neuromorphic architectural fit for transformer inference (dense matmuls, softmax, autoregressive decode)", "stances": [{"model": "google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview", "stance": "Suggests a fundamental mismatch (neuromorphic excels at sparse/event-driven workloads; transformers are dense/synchronous), so parity claims often rely on modified models/assumptions."}, {"model": "x-ai/grok-4.3", "stance": "Notes the conflict as a frequent issue but frames it as an engineering/benchmarking risk (e.g., softmax/attention inefficiency, assumed sparsity) rather than a strict impossibility."}]}, {"topic": "Response completeness (non-answer vs substantive criteria)", "stances": [{"model": "openai/gpt-5.2", "stance": "Provides no evaluation criteria; only states inability to use a tool."}, {"model": "google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview", "stance": "Provides substantive documentation requirements and common failure modes."}, {"model": "x-ai/grok-4.3", "stance": "Provides substantive documentation requirements and common failure modes."}]}], "partial_coverage": [{"models": ["x-ai/grok-4.3"], "point": "Calls out process node/die size/on-chip memory hierarchy as required context for energy-efficiency plausibility; mentions spike-encoding overheads as a neuromorphic-specific accounting item."}, {"models": ["google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview"], "point": "Explicitly demands a mapping strategy for attention/softmax/autoregressive decoding onto spiking/analog primitives and warns about projecting from tiny tiles to multi-chip systems without interconnect energy."}, {"models": ["google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview", "x-ai/grok-4.3"], "point": "Emphasize software-stack/compilation/reproducibility needs (open benchmark code, ability to run standard PyTorch/TensorRT-like graphs, avoidance of hand-tuned one-off demos) as a common place claims fail."}, {"models": ["x-ai/grok-4.3"], "point": "Explicitly requests third-party/independent validation and NDA-free reproducibility as a seriousness threshold."}], "unique_insights": [{"model": "x-ai/grok-4.3", "insight": "Neuromorphic-specific “spike encoding overhead” should be accounted for in throughput and energy: if continuous activations/attention are encoded into spikes/events, the representation overhead can erase claimed gains unless rigorously measured end-to-end."}], "blind_spots": ["No model pins down what “equivalent throughput” must mean for LLMs (separating prefill vs decode, tokens/s at a specified latency SLO, context length, batch size distribution, and real serving traces). This is often where claims hide (e.g., enormous batch with unusable latency).", "None demand a strict baseline definition for H100 (exact GPU SKU 80GB vs 94GB, power limit, clocks, TensorRT-LLM version, KV-cache precision, FP8/INT8 usage, kernel fusions, speculative decoding). Without this, “1000× vs H100” can be a strawman baseline.", "Insufficient attention to accuracy comparability: not just “no perplexity drop,” but task-level evals under the same quantization/approximation, including robustness across prompts and long-context behavior; also reporting calibration/drift effects for analog/spiking implementations.", "No one explicitly requires inclusion of KV-cache memory traffic/energy (often dominant in decode at long context) and how/where KV-cache is stored (HBM/DDR/SRAM) for the claimed regime.", "No discussion of measurement protocol details needed to prevent power-reporting artifacts (wall-plug vs rail power, sampling rate, warm-up/steady-state, inclusion of PSU losses, cooling/pumps/fans if comparing system energy, confidence intervals across runs).", "No deep treatment of scalability and packaging constraints: multi-chip partition strategy,