{"consensus": ["DAC at ~420 ppm requires processing very large air volumes per tCO2 captured (order ~10^3–10^4 tonnes of air per tonne CO2), so contactor pressure drop/fan energy and mass-transfer limits are first-order constraints at scale (verified by NASEM NETs 2018 energy breakdowns and multiple DAC engineering analyses).", ""Solar-only" energy supply introduces intermittency; without storage or major oversizing it reduces capacity factor and tends to raise levelized $/t because CAPEX is amortized over fewer operating hours (consistent with standard project-finance/TEA practice and renewable capacity factors).", "Gigaton-scale deployment is constrained by more than the capture material itself: it implies massive buildout of hardware, energy supply, and CO2 handling infrastructure (compression, transport, and durable storage), each of which can dominate cost and schedule (consistent with IEA/NASEM framing of DACCS system requirements).", "Lab or prototype performance is unlikely to extrapolate directly: durability under real air (humidity swings, contaminants, particulates), maintenance, and replacement rates can dominate long-run cost and performance (supported by known sorbent degradation/fouling challenges discussed broadly in DAC literature and field experience)."], "contradictions": [{"topic": "Whether the claim would require violating/surpassing thermodynamic (second-law) limits", "stances": [{"model": "google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview", "stance": "Frames the claim as highly improbable under current thermodynamic paradigms and implies thermodynamic constraints are near-binding for $500/t at high capture."}, {"model": "x-ai/grok-4.3", "stance": "States the claim would require thermodynamic limits to be surpassed or ignored in practice."}, {"model": "evidence", "stance": "Thermodynamics sets a lower bound but does not rule out low dollar costs in principle: minimum work is ~0.45–0.5 GJ/tCO2 (~125–140 kWh/t) for typical capture specs (e.g., NASEM reports ~20 kJ/mol), so the barrier is practical irreversibility, CAPEX, and system integration—not violating the second law."}]}, {"topic": "Magnitude/character of the energy penalty for pushing capture fraction toward ~95%", "stances": [{"model": "google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview", "stance": "Suggests energy/cost rises sharply (described as effectively ‘exponential’) as capture approaches very high fraction due to reduced driving force."}, {"model": "x-ai/grok-4.3", "stance": "Does not quantify; generally treats high efficiency as thermodynamically problematic."}, {"model": "evidence", "stance": "Minimum work increases roughly logarithmically with separation ratio and depends on outlet specs; practical energy can increase strongly because of kinetics/pressure drop/heat management, but calling it ‘exponential thermodynamic energy’ is not generally correct (separation work scales with ln terms; irreversibility and equipment sizing drive steep practical penalties)."}]}, {"topic": "Implied fan/air-handling burden at gigaton scale (order-of-magnitude claims)", "stances": [{"model": "google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview", "stance": "Claims ~2–3 trillion tons of air must be moved per gigaton CO2 and that fan power would be ‘astronomical’."}, {"model": "x-ai/grok-4.3", "stance": "Agrees air-moving burden is immense but provides no numbers."}, {"model": "evidence", "stance": "Air mass per tCO2 is ~1/CO2 mass fraction ≈ 1/(~0.0006–0.0007) ≈ 1,500–1,700 t air per tCO2, i.e., ~1.5–1.7 trillion tons of air per GtCO2 (same order, but 2–3T is high); fan energy depends on pressure drop and can be large but is not necessarily ‘astronomical’ relative to global energy (NASEM gives mid-range fan electricity on the order of ~0.55–1.12 GJ/tCO2 for solid sorbents)."}]}, {"topic": "Whether $50/t is being treated as total system cost vs marginal/operating cost", "stances": [{"model": "google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview", "stance": "Argues $50/t likely reflects lab-scale marginal operating cost and omits CAPEX, degradation, and compression."}, {"model": "x-ai/grok-4.3", "stance": "States cost claims are rarely validated beyond lab scale but does not distinguish CAPEX vs OPEX explicitly."}, {"model": "evidence", "stance": "Current public market pricing and many TEAs place DACCS far above $50/t today (often hundreds of $/t); however, it is not logically impossible for OPEX-alone to approach $50/t under optimistic energy and efficiency assumptions—so any evaluation must clarify accounting boundaries (gross vs net removal, CAPEX included, financing assumptions, storage included)."}]}], "partial_coverage": [{"models": ["google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview"], "point": "Notes that very high single-pass capture (e.g., 95%) may be economically non-optimal versus lower capture fractions due to mass-transfer/energy tradeoffs."}, {"models": ["google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview", "x-ai/grok-4.3"], "point": "Highlights sorbent supply-chain and scaling bottlenecks (availability of precursor chemicals/metals, manufacturing scale, and embodied impacts)."}, {"models": ["google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview"], "point": "Calls out downstream CO2 compression/transport/storage as potentially adding large additional cost beyond capture."}, {"models": ["google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview", "x-ai/grok-4.3"], "point": "Mentions land-use, permitting, and regulatory constraints as important for gigaton deployment, but without detailed quantification."}, {"models": ["google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview"], "point": "Raises water/humidity interactions (co-adsorption of water, stripping loads) and dust fouling risk for desert solar siting."}], "unique_insights": [{"model": "google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview", "insight": "Treating “95% capture efficiency” as a red flag because high single-pass capture can be economically suboptimal in dilute separations; optimizing $/t can favor lower capture fractions with smaller contactors and lower pressure drop."}], "blind_spots": ["Ambiguity of “95% efficiency”: efficiency of what (single-pass capture fraction, sorbent utilization, energy efficiency vs thermodynamic minimum, or net CO2 removed after lifecycle emissions)? None of the models force a precise definition or propose a measurement protocol.", "Net-removal accounting and MRV: how the team proves net-negative removal including PV manufacture, sorbent manufacture, replacements, maintenance logistics, and end-of-life disposal; panel gestures at LCA but does not specify required data/standards.", "Heat vs electricity form-factor: many DAC concepts need substantial low-grade heat; “solar-only” could mean PV electricity, solar thermal, or both, with very different efficiencies/costs and storage options—this is not interrogated.", "Financing and cost of capital: $/t at gigaton scale is highly sensitive to WACC, plant lifetime, uptime, and learning curves; models mention CAPEX qualitatively but do not ask for specific financing assumptions or bankability evidence.", "Storage permanence and capacity: geologic storage site availability, injectivity limits, monitoring for leakage, and the pace of Class VI permitting/buildout; models mention “storage” but not the hard deployment constraint at Gt/yr.", "System-level integration constraints at Gt/yr: supply chains for fans, contactors, compressors, pipelines, wells; workforce and construction rates; grid interconnection (even for solar-only, to build and operate auxiliaries).", "Performance under realistic atmospheric contaminants: ozone, SOx/NOx, aerosols, organics, sea salt; models mention poisoning in passing but do not specify test conditions, acceptable degradation rates, or mitigation costs.", "Spatial/temporal mismatch: where high solar resource coincides (or not) with viable storage basins and water availability; transport distances and their cost/energy are not analyzed.", "Opportunity cost of solar energy: whether using scarce clean electricity/land for DAC is optimal compared with direct decarbonization, and how that affects real-world adoption at scale."], "re