{"consensus": ["Dengue virus has 4 confirmed serotypes: DENV-1, DENV-2, DENV-3, DENV-4 (supported by current public-health references such as CDC and PAHO).", "Secondary infection with a different (heterologous) serotype is associated with higher risk of severe dengue, largely explained by antibody-dependent enhancement (ADE): pre-existing cross-reactive but insufficiently neutralizing antibodies can increase infection of Fc-receptor–bearing immune cells, raising viremia and inflammatory/vascular-leak pathology."], "contradictions": [{"topic": "Whether heterologous secondary infection is inherently/typically more severe vs a probabilistic risk factor (severe dengue can also occur in primary infection)", "stances": [{"model": "openai/gpt-5.2", "stance": "Frames as a main reason a second infection with a different serotype can be more severe (risk-oriented language, but still implies a general mechanism explanation)."}, {"model": "google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview", "stance": "Says a secondary infection with a different serotype typically causes more severe disease (stronger implication of typicality)."}, {"model": "x-ai/grok-4.3", "stance": "Explicitly notes risk is higher on second infection but severe dengue can occur on first or later infections too."}, {"model": "evidence", "stance": "Epidemiology and clinical guidance describe heterologous secondary infection as an important risk factor, not a necessary or sufficient cause; severe dengue also occurs in some primary infections (and in infants with waning maternal antibodies)."}]}], "partial_coverage": [{"models": ["openai/gpt-5.2", "google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview"], "point": "Mentions cross-reactive T-cell phenomena ('original antigenic sin') as an additional contributor to severity beyond ADE."}, {"models": ["openai/gpt-5.2", "google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview"], "point": "Specifies Fcγ/Fc receptors on monocytes/macrophages/dendritic cells as the cellular route exploited in ADE (mechanistic detail not consistently present in all responses)."}, {"models": ["google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview", "x-ai/grok-4.3"], "point": "States lifelong immunity is serotype-specific with only short-lived cross-protection to other serotypes after primary infection."}, {"models": ["openai/gpt-5.2", "google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview"], "point": "Adds the caveat that 'DENV-5' has been proposed in the literature but is not broadly accepted as a confirmed, routinely circulating human serotype."}], "unique_insights": [{"model": "x-ai/grok-4.3", "insight": "Makes the important nuance explicit that although heterologous secondary infection is a major risk factor, severe dengue is not exclusive to second infections (it can occur in primary or later infections depending on context)."}], "blind_spots": ["No response clearly distinguishes 'confirmed serotypes' (DENV-1–4) from ongoing debates about what would count as formal recognition (e.g., ICTV taxonomy vs antigenic/neutralization-defined serotypes) and why DENV-5 remains 'putative' in many modern summaries.", "None discuss the antibody-titer/time-interval dependence of ADE (cross-protection early after first infection vs higher risk later as neutralizing titers wane), which is central to why secondary infections are not uniformly severe.", "None mention severe dengue in infants driven by waning maternal anti-DENV antibodies (a classic ADE context) as supporting evidence for the mechanism.", "No response covers NS1’s role and endothelial glycocalyx/complement interactions (and anti-NS1 effects) as additional, evidence-backed contributors to vascular leak alongside ADE.", "No response addresses viral and host heterogeneity that modulates severity (viral genotype/strain virulence, prior infection sequence, host genetics/HLA, age, pregnancy, comorbidities), which are important for a truth-seeking explanation beyond a single mechanism."], "responses": [{"model": "openai/gpt-5.2", "content": "The dengue virus has **4 confirmed serotypes**:

1. **DENV-1** (Dengue virus serotype 1)  
2. **DENV-2** (Dengue virus serotype 2)  
3. **DENV-3** (Dengue virus serotype 3)  
4. **DENV-4** (Dengue virus serotype 4)

(Some papers have discussed a possible “DENV-5,” but the widely accepted, confirmed human dengue serotypes remain **1–4**.)

## Why a second infection with a *different* serotype can be more severe
The main reason is **antibody-dependent enhancement (ADE)**, plus related immunologic effects:

